Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: KenolKobil, Naiade Resorts, Starcomms

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-13T16:05:02Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-13/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenolkobil-naiade-resorts-starcomms.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index climbed 0.2
percent to 2,108.62 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis , the
highest since at least 1989.  Kenya’s All-Share Index rose for the first day in five,
climbing 0.3 percent to 75.87 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.
 Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  snapped two days of losses,
rising 1.2 percent to 852 by the 4 p.m. end of trading in
Windhoek. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index advanced
0.3 percent, the fourth days of gains, to 25,813.71 by the 2:30
p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed statement from the
exchange. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index rose for a
second day, up 0.3 percent to 1,155.06 at the 3 p.m. close of
trading in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in nine African nations, gained 5 cents, or 0.5
percent, to 9.35 shillings, after the Nairobi-based company won
a contract to supply 36,355 metric tons of diesel to the East
African nation’s Energy Ministry.  Naiade Resorts Ltd. (NRL)  , Mauritius’s third-largest
hotel operator by market value, rallied 2.4 percent to 34
rupees, the highest level since January 2010. Chief Executive
Officer  Paul Jones  said the group will return to profit in the
year through June. Room occupancy for April increased to 80
percent from 61 percent a year earlier, he said.  Starcomms Plc (STARCOMM)  , a Nigerian company that offers
fixed-line and mobile-telephone services, snapped two days of
gains, losing 2 kobo, or 2.6 percent, to 76 kobo, after
reporting a loss of 7.7 billion naira ($49 million) for the year
through December, compared with a loss of 7.8 billion naira a
year earlier.  United Basalt Products (UBP)  Ltd, a Mauritian building
materials manufacturer and retailer, retreated 1 rupee, or 0.7
percent, to 144 rupee, its biggest decline since March 24. Net
income dropped to 17.7 million rupees ($638,000) in the third
quarter through March, from 55.3 million rupees the same period
a year earlier, the company said in a statement published after
the end of trading yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
